{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"My title: \"Queerer than we can\nsuppose: the strangeness of science.\""},{"time":6416,"text":"\"Queerer than we can suppose\" comes\nfrom J.B.S. Haldane, the famous biologist,"},{"time":10582,"text":"who said, \"Now, my own suspicion\nis that the universe is not only queerer"},{"time":15384,"text":"than we suppose, but queerer\nthan we can suppose."},{"time":19848,"text":"I suspect that there are more things\nin heaven and earth"},{"time":22603,"text":"than are dreamed of, or can\nbe dreamed of, in any philosophy.\""},{"time":29213,"text":"Richard Feynman compared\nthe accuracy of quantum theories --"},{"time":34052,"text":"experimental predictions --"},{"time":35902,"text":"to specifying the width of North America\nto within one hair's breadth of accuracy."},{"time":42649,"text":"This means that quantum theory\nhas got to be, in some sense, true."},{"time":46742,"text":"Yet the assumptions\nthat quantum theory needs to make"},{"time":49701,"text":"in order to deliver those\npredictions are so mysterious"},{"time":53164,"text":"that even Feynman himself\nwas moved to remark,"},{"time":56942,"text":"\"If you think you understand\nquantum theory,"},{"time":59805,"text":"you don't understand quantum theory.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":63670,"text":"It's so queer that physicists\nresort to one or another"},{"time":67100,"text":"paradoxical interpretation of it."},{"time":70378,"text":"David Deutsch, who's talking here,\nin \"The Fabric of Reality,\""},{"time":74895,"text":"embraces the many-worlds\ninterpretation of quantum theory,"},{"time":80000,"text":"because the worst that you\ncan say about it"},{"time":82045,"text":"is that it's preposterously wasteful."},{"time":84322,"text":"It postulates a vast and rapidly growing\nnumber of universes existing in parallel,"},{"time":90751,"text":"mutually undetectable,"},{"time":92586,"text":"except through the narrow porthole\nof quantum mechanical experiments."},{"time":100268,"text":"And that's Richard Feynman."}]},{"cues":[{"time":103395,"text":"The biologist Lewis Wolpert believes"},{"time":105793,"text":"that the queerness of modern physics"},{"time":107532,"text":"is just an extreme example."},{"time":109242,"text":"Science, as opposed to technology,"},{"time":111566,"text":"does violence to common sense."},{"time":114787,"text":"Every time you drink a glass\nof water, he points out,"},{"time":117914,"text":"the odds are that you will imbibe\nat least one molecule"},{"time":121419,"text":"that passed through the bladder\nof Oliver Cromwell."},{"time":124401,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":126232,"text":"It's just elementary probability theory."}]},{"cues":[{"time":128483,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":129683,"text":"The number of molecules\nper glassful is hugely greater"},{"time":132924,"text":"than the number of glassfuls,\nor bladdersful, in the world."},{"time":136734,"text":"And of course, there's nothing special\nabout Cromwell or bladders --"},{"time":139968,"text":"you have just breathed in a nitrogen atom"},{"time":142421,"text":"that passed through the right lung\nof the third iguanodon"},{"time":146000,"text":"to the left of the tall cycad tree."}]},{"cues":[{"time":151555,"text":"\"Queerer than we can suppose.\""},{"time":154807,"text":"What is it that makes us\ncapable of supposing anything,"},{"time":158350,"text":"and does this tell us anything\nabout what we can suppose?"},{"time":162724,"text":"Are there things about the universe\nthat will be forever beyond our grasp,"},{"time":168106,"text":"but not beyond the grasp\nof some superior intelligence?"},{"time":171497,"text":"Are there things about the universe"},{"time":173210,"text":"that are, in principle,\nungraspable by any mind,"},{"time":177481,"text":"however superior?"},{"time":180422,"text":"The history of science has been\none long series of violent brainstorms,"},{"time":185183,"text":"as successive generations\nhave come to terms with"},{"time":188307,"text":"increasing levels of queerness\nin the universe."},{"time":191863,"text":"We're now so used to the idea\nthat the Earth spins,"},{"time":194937,"text":"rather than the Sun moves across the sky,"},{"time":197292,"text":"it's hard for us to realize"},{"time":198625,"text":"what a shattering mental revolution\nthat must have been."},{"time":202631,"text":"After all, it seems obvious\nthat the Earth is large and motionless,"},{"time":205858,"text":"the Sun, small and mobile."},{"time":207661,"text":"But it's worth recalling\nWittgenstein's remark on the subject:"},{"time":212270,"text":"\"Tell me,\" he asked a friend,\n\"why do people always say"},{"time":216273,"text":"it was natural for man to assume\nthat the Sun went 'round the Earth,"},{"time":220372,"text":"rather than that the Earth was rotating?\""},{"time":223878,"text":"And his friend replied, \"Well, obviously,"},{"time":225895,"text":"because it just looks as though\nthe Sun is going round the Earth.\""},{"time":230114,"text":"Wittgenstein replied, \"Well,\nwhat would it have looked like"},{"time":233900,"text":"if it had looked as though\nthe Earth was rotating?\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":237436,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":242000,"text":"Science has taught us,\nagainst all intuition,"},{"time":245051,"text":"that apparently solid things,\nlike crystals and rocks,"},{"time":248476,"text":"are really almost entirely\ncomposed of empty space."},{"time":252706,"text":"And the familiar illustration\nis the nucleus of an atom"},{"time":257025,"text":"is a fly in the middle\nof a sports stadium,"},{"time":260164,"text":"and the next atom\nis in the next sports stadium."},{"time":263897,"text":"So it would seem the hardest,\nsolidest, densest rock"},{"time":267108,"text":"is really almost entirely empty space,"},{"time":270721,"text":"broken only by tiny particles\nso widely spaced they shouldn't count."},{"time":275835,"text":"Why, then, do rocks look and feel\nsolid and hard and impenetrable?"},{"time":281199,"text":"As an evolutionary biologist,\nI'd say this: our brains have evolved"},{"time":285898,"text":"to help us survive within the orders\nof magnitude, of size and speed"},{"time":292000,"text":"which our bodies operate at."},{"time":294185,"text":"We never evolved to navigate\nin the world of atoms."},{"time":297092,"text":"If we had, our brains\nprobably would perceive rocks"},{"time":300441,"text":"as full of empty space."},{"time":301911,"text":"Rocks feel hard and impenetrable"},{"time":304379,"text":"to our hands, precisely because\nobjects like rocks and hands"},{"time":309000,"text":"cannot penetrate each other."},{"time":311537,"text":"It's therefore useful"},{"time":313353,"text":"for our brains to construct notions\nlike \"solidity\" and \"impenetrability,\""},{"time":319503,"text":"because such notions help us\nto navigate our bodies"},{"time":323000,"text":"through the middle-sized world\nin which we have to navigate."}]},{"cues":[{"time":327644,"text":"Moving to the other end of the scale,"},{"time":329445,"text":"our ancestors never had to navigate\nthrough the cosmos"},{"time":332859,"text":"at speeds close to the speed of light."},{"time":335247,"text":"If they had, our brains would be\nmuch better at understanding Einstein."},{"time":340765,"text":"I want to give the name \"Middle World\"\nto the medium-scaled environment"},{"time":345290,"text":"in which we've evolved\nthe ability to take act --"},{"time":347712,"text":"nothing to do with \"Middle Earth\" --"},{"time":349463,"text":"Middle World."}]},{"cues":[{"time":350638,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":352000,"text":"We are evolved denizens of Middle World,"},{"time":355033,"text":"and that limits what\nwe are capable of imagining."},{"time":358533,"text":"We find it intuitively easy\nto grasp ideas like,"},{"time":361338,"text":"when a rabbit moves\nat the sort of medium velocity"},{"time":364127,"text":"at which rabbits and other\nMiddle World objects move,"},{"time":367000,"text":"and hits another Middle World object\nlike a rock, it knocks itself out."}]},{"cues":[{"time":372846,"text":"May I introduce Major General\nAlbert Stubblebine III,"},{"time":378632,"text":"commander of military\nintelligence in 1983."}]},{"cues":[{"time":383651,"text":"\"...[He] stared at his wall in Arlington,\nVirginia, and decided to do it."},{"time":389445,"text":"As frightening as the prospect was,\nhe was going into the next office."},{"time":395238,"text":"He stood up and moved\nout from behind his desk."},{"time":400088,"text":"'What is the atom mostly made of?'\nhe thought, 'Space.'"},{"time":404428,"text":"He started walking. 'What am I\nmostly made of? Atoms.'"},{"time":410340,"text":"He quickened his pace,\nalmost to a jog now."},{"time":413181,"text":"'What is the wall mostly made of?'"}]},{"cues":[{"time":415550,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":416575,"text":"'Atoms!'"},{"time":418588,"text":"All I have to do is merge the spaces."},{"time":423056,"text":"Then, General Stubblebine banged\nhis nose hard on the wall of his office."},{"time":429339,"text":"Stubblebine, who commanded\n16,000 soldiers,"},{"time":433302,"text":"was confounded by his continual failure\nto walk through the wall."},{"time":437253,"text":"He has no doubt that this ability\nwill one day be a common tool"},{"time":440345,"text":"in the military arsenal."},{"time":441996,"text":"Who would screw around with an army\nthat could do that?\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":445835,"text":"That's from an article in Playboy,"},{"time":447828,"text":"which I was reading the other day."}]},{"cues":[{"time":449567,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":451198,"text":"I have every reason to think it's true;"},{"time":453118,"text":"I was reading Playboy because I, myself,\nhad an article in it."}]},{"cues":[{"time":456630,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":462515,"text":"Unaided human intuition,\nschooled in Middle World,"},{"time":467189,"text":"finds it hard to believe Galileo\nwhen he tells us"},{"time":470520,"text":"a heavy object and a light object,\nair friction aside,"},{"time":473938,"text":"would hit the ground at the same instant."},{"time":475938,"text":"And that's because in Middle World,\nair friction is always there."},{"time":479516,"text":"If we'd evolved in a vacuum,"},{"time":480889,"text":"we would expect them to hit\nthe ground simultaneously."},{"time":484106,"text":"If we were bacteria,"},{"time":485643,"text":"constantly buffeted by thermal\nmovements of molecules,"},{"time":488982,"text":"it would be different."},{"time":490157,"text":"But we Middle-Worlders are too big\nto notice Brownian motion."},{"time":493856,"text":"In the same way, our lives\nare dominated by gravity,"},{"time":497230,"text":"but are almost oblivious\nto the force of surface tension."},{"time":500851,"text":"A small insect would reverse\nthese priorities."}]},{"cues":[{"time":505067,"text":"Steve Grand -- he's the one on the left,"},{"time":507544,"text":"Douglas Adams is on the right."},{"time":509123,"text":"Steve Grand, in his book,\n\"Creation: Life and How to Make It,\""},{"time":512845,"text":"is positively scathing about our\npreoccupation with matter itself."},{"time":518698,"text":"We have this tendency to think\nthat only solid, material things"},{"time":522361,"text":"are really things at all."},{"time":524811,"text":"Waves of electromagnetic fluctuation\nin a vacuum seem unreal."},{"time":529750,"text":"Victorians thought the waves\nhad to be waves in some material medium:"},{"time":534620,"text":"the ether."},{"time":536380,"text":"But we find real matter comforting"},{"time":538771,"text":"only because we've evolved\nto survive in Middle World,"},{"time":542762,"text":"where matter is a useful fiction."},{"time":546000,"text":"A whirlpool, for Steve Grand,\nis a thing with just as much reality"},{"time":550262,"text":"as a rock."}]},{"cues":[{"time":552978,"text":"In a desert plain in Tanzania,"},{"time":555652,"text":"in the shadow of the volcano\nOl Doinyo Lengai,"},{"time":558866,"text":"there's a dune made of volcanic ash."},{"time":561651,"text":"The beautiful thing\nis that it moves bodily."},{"time":565000,"text":"It's what's technically known\nas a \"barchan,\""},{"time":567231,"text":"and the entire dune walks\nacross the desert in a westerly direction"},{"time":571459,"text":"at a speed of about 17 meters per year."},{"time":574825,"text":"It retains its crescent shape and moves\nin the direction of the horns."},{"time":579340,"text":"What happens is that the wind blows\nthe sand up the shallow slope"},{"time":583340,"text":"on the other side,"},{"time":584572,"text":"and then, as each sand grain hits\nthe top of the ridge, it cascades down"},{"time":588341,"text":"on the inside of the crescent,"},{"time":589823,"text":"and so the whole horn-shaped dune moves."},{"time":594803,"text":"Steve Grand points out\nthat you and I are, ourselves,"},{"time":598317,"text":"more like a wave than a permanent thing."},{"time":601877,"text":"He invites us, the reader,"},{"time":603752,"text":"to think of an experience\nfrom your childhood,"},{"time":606181,"text":"something you remember clearly,"},{"time":607763,"text":"something you can see,\nfeel, maybe even smell,"},{"time":610821,"text":"as if you were really there."},{"time":612560,"text":"After all, you really were there\nat the time, weren't you?"},{"time":616357,"text":"How else would you remember it?"},{"time":618485,"text":"But here is the bombshell:\nYou weren't there."},{"time":621167,"text":"Not a single atom\nthat is in your body today"},{"time":623608,"text":"was there when that event took place."},{"time":626142,"text":"Matter flows from place to place"},{"time":628309,"text":"and momentarily comes together to be you."},{"time":631261,"text":"Whatever you are, therefore,"},{"time":632637,"text":"you are not the stuff\nof which you are made."},{"time":636743,"text":"If that doesn't make the hair stand up\non the back of your neck,"},{"time":639815,"text":"read it again until it does,\nbecause it is important."}]},{"cues":[{"time":644283,"text":"So \"really\" isn't a word that we should\nuse with simple confidence."},{"time":649000,"text":"If a neutrino had a brain,"},{"time":651296,"text":"which it evolved\nin neutrino-sized ancestors,"},{"time":654062,"text":"it would say that rocks really\ndo consist of empty space."},{"time":658833,"text":"We have brains that evolved\nin medium-sized ancestors"},{"time":661650,"text":"which couldn't walk through rocks."},{"time":664030,"text":"\"Really,\" for an animal, is whatever\nits brain needs it to be"},{"time":668674,"text":"in order to assist its survival."},{"time":671075,"text":"And because different species\nlive in different worlds,"},{"time":673846,"text":"there will be a discomforting\nvariety of \"reallys.\""},{"time":680370,"text":"What we see of the real world\nis not the unvarnished world,"},{"time":684631,"text":"but a model of the world,\nregulated and adjusted by sense data,"},{"time":688936,"text":"but constructed so it's useful\nfor dealing with the real world."}]},{"cues":[{"time":693459,"text":"The nature of the model depends\non the kind of animal we are."},{"time":697000,"text":"A flying animal needs\na different kind of model"},{"time":700657,"text":"from a walking, climbing\nor swimming animal."},{"time":703381,"text":"A monkey's brain must have\nsoftware capable of simulating"},{"time":707825,"text":"a three-dimensional world\nof branches and trunks."},{"time":711144,"text":"A mole's software for constructing models\nof its world will be customized"},{"time":715545,"text":"for underground use."},{"time":717521,"text":"A water strider's brain\ndoesn't need 3D software at all,"},{"time":721412,"text":"since it lives on the surface of the pond,"},{"time":723586,"text":"in an Edwin Abbott flatland."}]},{"cues":[{"time":727652,"text":"I've speculated that bats may see\ncolor with their ears."},{"time":732390,"text":"The world model that a bat needs\nin order to navigate"},{"time":735608,"text":"through three dimensions catching insects"},{"time":737609,"text":"must be pretty similar to the world\nmodel that any flying bird --"},{"time":740706,"text":"a day-flying bird like a swallow --\nneeds to perform the same kind of tasks."},{"time":745000,"text":"The fact that the bat uses\nechoes in pitch darkness"},{"time":748314,"text":"to input the current\nvariables to its model,"},{"time":751105,"text":"while the swallow uses\nlight, is incidental."},{"time":754456,"text":"Bats, I've even suggested, use\nperceived hues, such as red and blue,"},{"time":759758,"text":"as labels, internal labels,\nfor some useful aspect of echoes --"},{"time":765897,"text":"perhaps the acoustic texture of surfaces,\nfurry or smooth and so on --"},{"time":770468,"text":"in the same way as swallows or indeed,\nwe, use those perceived hues --"},{"time":775055,"text":"redness and blueness, etc. --"},{"time":776683,"text":"to label long and short\nwavelengths of light."},{"time":779579,"text":"There's nothing inherent about red\nthat makes it long wavelength."}]},{"cues":[{"time":783747,"text":"The point is that the nature of the model\nis governed by how it is to be used,"},{"time":787995,"text":"rather than by the sensory\nmodality involved."},{"time":792871,"text":"J.B.S. Haldane himself had\nsomething to say about animals"},{"time":795715,"text":"whose world is dominated by smell."},{"time":798535,"text":"Dogs can distinguish two very similar\nfatty acids, extremely diluted:"},{"time":804393,"text":"caprylic acid and caproic acid."},{"time":807101,"text":"The only difference, you see,"},{"time":808523,"text":"is that one has an extra pair\nof carbon atoms in the chain."},{"time":811831,"text":"Haldane guesses that a dog would probably\nbe able to place the acids"},{"time":816343,"text":"in the order of their molecular\nweights by their smells,"},{"time":819811,"text":"just as a man could place\na number of piano wires"},{"time":822957,"text":"in the order of their lengths\nby means of their notes."},{"time":826726,"text":"Now, there's another\nfatty acid, capric acid,"},{"time":830537,"text":"which is just like the other two,"},{"time":832173,"text":"except that it has two more carbon atoms."},{"time":835481,"text":"A dog that had never met\ncapric acid would, perhaps,"},{"time":838328,"text":"have no more trouble imagining its smell"},{"time":841305,"text":"than we would have trouble\nimagining a trumpet, say,"},{"time":844485,"text":"playing one note higher than we've heard\na trumpet play before."},{"time":851549,"text":"Perhaps dogs and rhinos and other\nsmell-oriented animals smell in color."},{"time":858268,"text":"And the argument would be exactly\nthe same as for the bats."}]},{"cues":[{"time":863253,"text":"Middle World -- the range\nof sizes and speeds"},{"time":866964,"text":"which we have evolved to feel\nintuitively comfortable with --"},{"time":870576,"text":"is a bit like the narrow range\nof the electromagnetic spectrum"},{"time":874368,"text":"that we see as light of various colors."},{"time":877220,"text":"We're blind to all\nfrequencies outside that,"},{"time":879564,"text":"unless we use instruments to help us."},{"time":884000,"text":"Middle World is the narrow\nrange of reality"},{"time":887166,"text":"which we judge to be normal,\nas opposed to the queerness"},{"time":890444,"text":"of the very small, the very large\nand the very fast."},{"time":895000,"text":"We could make a similar\nscale of improbabilities;"},{"time":897873,"text":"nothing is totally impossible."},{"time":900508,"text":"Miracles are just events\nthat are extremely improbable."},{"time":904230,"text":"A marble statue could wave its hand at us;"},{"time":907083,"text":"the atoms that make up\nits crystalline structure"},{"time":909970,"text":"are all vibrating back and forth anyway."},{"time":912211,"text":"Because there are so many of them,"},{"time":913893,"text":"and because there's no\nagreement among them"},{"time":916000,"text":"in their preferred direction of movement,"},{"time":918100,"text":"the marble, as we see it\nin Middle World, stays rock steady."},{"time":922189,"text":"But the atoms in the hand\ncould all just happen to move"},{"time":924823,"text":"the same way at the same time,\nand again and again."},{"time":927471,"text":"In this case, the hand would move,"},{"time":929144,"text":"and we'd see it waving at us\nin Middle World."},{"time":932951,"text":"The odds against it,\nof course, are so great"},{"time":935561,"text":"that if you set out writing zeros\nat the time of the origin of the universe,"},{"time":940065,"text":"you still would not have written\nenough zeros to this day."}]},{"cues":[{"time":944206,"text":"Evolution in Middle World\nhas not equipped us"},{"time":947258,"text":"to handle very improbable events;\nwe don't live long enough."},{"time":951497,"text":"In the vastness of astronomical space\nand geological time,"},{"time":956212,"text":"that which seems impossible\nin Middle World"},{"time":959034,"text":"might turn out to be inevitable."},{"time":963135,"text":"One way to think about that\nis by counting planets."},{"time":966724,"text":"We don't know how many planets\nthere are in the universe,"},{"time":969430,"text":"but a good estimate is about 10 to the 20,\nor 100 billion billion."},{"time":973374,"text":"And that gives us a nice way to express\nour estimate of life's improbability."},{"time":979710,"text":"We could make some sort of landmark points\nalong a spectrum of improbability,"},{"time":983427,"text":"which might look like the electromagnetic\nspectrum we just looked at."}]},{"cues":[{"time":988568,"text":"If life has arisen only once on any --"},{"time":992850,"text":"life could originate once per planet,\ncould be extremely common"},{"time":998097,"text":"or it could originate once per star"},{"time":1000685,"text":"or once per galaxy or maybe only\nonce in the entire universe,"},{"time":1005701,"text":"in which case it would have to be here."},{"time":1007910,"text":"And somewhere up there would be the chance"},{"time":1009985,"text":"that a frog would turn into a prince,"},{"time":1011810,"text":"and similar magical things like that."},{"time":1015207,"text":"If life has arisen on only one planet\nin the entire universe,"},{"time":1019099,"text":"that planet has to be our planet,\nbecause here we are talking about it."},{"time":1023119,"text":"And that means that if we want\nto avail ourselves of it,"},{"time":1025795,"text":"we're allowed to postulate chemical events\nin the origin of life"},{"time":1029656,"text":"which have a probability as low\nas one in 100 billion billion."},{"time":1034036,"text":"I don't think we shall have\nto avail ourselves of that,"},{"time":1036693,"text":"because I suspect that life\nis quite common in the universe."},{"time":1039684,"text":"And when I say quite common,\nit could still be so rare"},{"time":1042746,"text":"that no one island of life\never encounters another,"},{"time":1046895,"text":"which is a sad thought."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1049665,"text":"How shall we interpret\n\"queerer than we can suppose?\""},{"time":1053397,"text":"Queerer than can in principle be supposed,"},{"time":1055676,"text":"or just queerer than we can suppose,\ngiven the limitations"},{"time":1059138,"text":"of our brain's evolutionary\napprenticeship in Middle World?"},{"time":1064000,"text":"Could we, by training and practice,"},{"time":1065878,"text":"emancipate ourselves from Middle World"},{"time":1068092,"text":"and achieve some sort of intuitive\nas well as mathematical understanding"},{"time":1072759,"text":"of the very small and the very large?"},{"time":1074922,"text":"I genuinely don't know the answer."},{"time":1077058,"text":"I wonder whether we might help ourselves\nto understand, say, quantum theory,"},{"time":1080716,"text":"if we brought up children\nto play computer games"},{"time":1084000,"text":"beginning in early childhood,"},{"time":1085606,"text":"which had a make-believe world of balls\ngoing through two slits on a screen,"},{"time":1089551,"text":"a world in which the strange goings-on\nof quantum mechanics were enlarged"},{"time":1093563,"text":"by the computer's make-believe,"},{"time":1095481,"text":"so that they became familiar\non the Middle-World scale of the stream."},{"time":1099350,"text":"And similarly, a relativistic\ncomputer game,"},{"time":1101928,"text":"in which objects on the screen manifest\nthe Lorentz contraction, and so on,"},{"time":1107268,"text":"to try to get ourselves -- to get children\ninto the way of thinking about it."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1112124,"text":"I want to end by applying\nthe idea of Middle World"},{"time":1116029,"text":"to our perceptions of each other."},{"time":1118735,"text":"Most scientists today subscribe\nto a mechanistic view of the mind:"},{"time":1123046,"text":"we're the way we are because our brains\nare wired up as they are,"},{"time":1126474,"text":"our hormones are the way they are."},{"time":1128150,"text":"We'd be different, our characters\nwould be different,"},{"time":1130685,"text":"if our neuro-anatomy and our\nphysiological chemistry were different."},{"time":1134868,"text":"But we scientists are inconsistent."},{"time":1137424,"text":"If we were consistent,"},{"time":1138829,"text":"our response to a misbehaving\nperson, like a child-murderer,"},{"time":1142166,"text":"should be something like:"},{"time":1143524,"text":"this unit has a faulty component;\nit needs repairing."},{"time":1146794,"text":"That's not what we say."},{"time":1148000,"text":"What we say -- and I include\nthe most austerely mechanistic among us,"},{"time":1152187,"text":"which is probably me --"},{"time":1153425,"text":"what we say is, \"Vile monster,\nprison is too good for you.\""},{"time":1157259,"text":"Or worse, we seek revenge,\nin all probability thereby triggering"},{"time":1161000,"text":"the next phase in an escalating\ncycle of counter-revenge,"},{"time":1164594,"text":"which we see, of course,\nall over the world today."},{"time":1167496,"text":"In short, when we're\nthinking like academics,"},{"time":1169796,"text":"we regard people as elaborate\nand complicated machines,"},{"time":1173119,"text":"like computers or cars."},{"time":1175663,"text":"But when we revert to being human,"},{"time":1177701,"text":"we behave more like Basil Fawlty,\nwho, we remember,"},{"time":1181436,"text":"thrashed his car to teach it a lesson,"},{"time":1183299,"text":"when it wouldn't start on \"Gourmet Night.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":1185598,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1187308,"text":"The reason we personify things\nlike cars and computers"},{"time":1191316,"text":"is that just as monkeys live\nin an arboreal world"},{"time":1194708,"text":"and moles live in an underground world"},{"time":1197394,"text":"and water striders live in a surface\ntension-dominated flatland,"},{"time":1201232,"text":"we live in a social world."},{"time":1203385,"text":"We swim through a sea of people --"},{"time":1205595,"text":"a social version of Middle World."},{"time":1208562,"text":"We are evolved to second-guess\nthe behavior of others"},{"time":1212301,"text":"by becoming brilliant,\nintuitive psychologists."},{"time":1216464,"text":"Treating people as machines"},{"time":1217880,"text":"may be scientifically\nand philosophically accurate,"},{"time":1221419,"text":"but it's a cumbersome waste of time"},{"time":1223356,"text":"if you want to guess what this person\nis going to do next."},{"time":1227000,"text":"The economically useful way\nto model a person"},{"time":1230000,"text":"is to treat him as a purposeful,\ngoal-seeking agent"},{"time":1233635,"text":"with pleasures and pains,\ndesires and intentions,"},{"time":1236075,"text":"guilt, blame-worthiness."},{"time":1238456,"text":"Personification and the imputing\nof intentional purpose"},{"time":1242590,"text":"is such a brilliantly successful\nway to model humans,"},{"time":1246257,"text":"it's hardly surprising\nthe same modeling software"},{"time":1249402,"text":"often seizes control when we're\ntrying to think about entities"},{"time":1253000,"text":"for which it's not appropriate,\nlike Basil Fawlty with his car"},{"time":1256395,"text":"or like millions of deluded people,\nwith the universe as a whole."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1261717,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1264000,"text":"If the universe is queerer\nthan we can suppose,"},{"time":1267165,"text":"is it just because\nwe've been naturally selected"},{"time":1269691,"text":"to suppose only what we needed to suppose"},{"time":1272684,"text":"in order to survive\nin the Pleistocene of Africa?"},{"time":1275863,"text":"Or are our brains so versatile\nand expandable that we can train ourselves"},{"time":1281587,"text":"to break out of the box of our evolution?"},{"time":1284909,"text":"Or finally, are there some things\nin the universe so queer"},{"time":1289346,"text":"that no philosophy of beings,\nhowever godlike, could dream them?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1295737,"text":"Thank you very much."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1296913,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}